english:
  title: A Royal Commendation for Minister Kim
  author: Choe Yuqing
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To the Court:

    He who stands at the center of power fulfills the duty of aiding his sovereign, and in placing the diligent upon the seat of ease, we honor the manner befitting a great minister. Though comings and goings shift with circumstance, the regard and affection bestowed remain constant and true.

    Behold Official Kim Buwil: his writing possesses grace enough to adorn all things; his learning penetrates the three realms of heaven, earth, and man. His wisdom brings benefit to this kingdom, and his merit moves heaven itself. When I sought counsel, he was foremost among those chosen. Rising through the Pivot Bureau, he ascended to the highest council, where he held fast to principle without wavering, and responded to all matters with growing clarity. His excellent strategies he brought forth, rising day and night in his devotion. My heart knows him alone, and thus our spirits have become as one. His reputation now shines brilliantly, and great accomplishments await his hand.

    Yet illness has afflicted him, and he grows resolute in his wish to retire. Repeatedly he has submitted his petitions with unwavering earnestness. He regards high office as one would regard scalding water, and abandons the burdens of state as one flees from a pit. Reflecting upon the attendants of former courts, some have changed with the times, yet among all ministers of steadfast virtue, none compare to him. Seeing how he wears himself thin in service, I am moved to compassion. Let him lay down his labors and nurture his years in peace.

    Therefore, I bestow upon him this extraordinary grace and rare honor: command of the military officials, stewardship of the Imperial Archives, the rank of Chief of the Open Government, and elevation to the title of Lord of Ten Thousand Households. His position encompasses both civil and military authority, his rank equal to the greatest ministers. This is a singular privilege befitting his clear wisdom and generous spirit.

    Alas, wealth and rank are only rightly held when aligned with the Way, and fame and merit are achieved when one's season arrives. He who moves at ease within the court can bring peace to all lands, and he who enters the halls of state becomes a model to the hundred officials. Go forth in your new office, and may you enjoy blessings without end.

    Let it be decreed: Kim Buwil is hereby appointed Chief of the Open Government, rank equal to the Three Excellencies, Grand Guardian, Director of the Imperial Secretariat, and Supreme Lord of Ten Thousand Households.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three realms' (三才) refers to heaven, earth, and humanity in classical Chinese cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Pivot Bureau' (樞府) was a high council of state in medieval East Asian governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The titles bestowed—'Chief of the Open Government,' 'Grand Guardian,' 'Lord of Ten Thousand Households'—were prestigious honorific positions that often carried retirement benefits.
  - key: ''
    value: This document is a formal royal decree (誥文), a genre used to announce and justify appointments and honors in classical East Asian courts.
